    desc: "アーレントの「悪の凡庸さ」を解説する哲学読み物。思考停止の危険。",
    text: `In 1961, the philosopher Hannah Arendt traveled to Jerusalem to report on the trial of Adolf Eichmann, a chief administrator of the Holocaust. She expected to confront a monster. What she found instead disturbed her far more profoundly, and produced one of the most contested phrases in modern thought: the banality of evil.

Eichmann, in Arendt's portrait, was not a sadist or an ideological fanatic. He was a careerist — an ambitious, rather mediocre bureaucrat who organized the transportation of millions to their deaths with the same diligence another man might bring to managing railway timetables. Asked to explain himself, he spoke in clichés and organizational jargon, repeatedly emphasizing that he had followed orders, broken no laws of his state, and merely done his job well. What struck Arendt was not the presence of hatred but the absence of thought. Eichmann, she argued, exhibited a near-total inability to consider his actions from the standpoint of those affected by them — a thoughtlessness so complete that it functioned as moral blindness.

Her thesis was widely misunderstood as excusing Eichmann or minimizing the Holocaust's horror, and historians have since argued that Eichmann was more ideologically committed than his courtroom performance suggested. Yet the core insight has only gained force with time. Arendt's claim was not that evil is trivial, but that catastrophic evil does not require demonic individuals. It can be assembled from ordinary ambition, conformity, deference to authority, and the comfortable refusal to think — distributed across thousands of functionaries, each handling one administrative fragment, none feeling responsible for the whole.

Subsequent psychology lent the thesis uncomfortable support. Milgram's obedience experiments found that a majority of ordinary volunteers would administer what they believed were dangerous electric shocks when instructed by an authority figure. The lesson is not that everyone is secretly wicked, but that situational forces — hierarchy, distance from consequences, incremental steps — can carry conventional people across moral lines they would never cross in a single leap.

Arendt's prescription was deceptively simple: thinking itself, the silent dialogue in which one examines one's own conduct, is a moral activity. The habit of stopping to think — particularly when institutions, careers, and crowds are all pushing forward — may be among the most underrated defenses a society possesses.

Evil, she warned, often arrives not with horns, but with a briefcase and excellent attendance.`,
