    desc: "セネカの時間論を現代の注意経済に接続する哲学エッセイ。",
    text: `Two thousand years ago, the Stoic philosopher Seneca opened his essay "On the Shortness of Life" with a diagnosis that reads as though written this morning: life is not short, he argued — we make it short by squandering it. Men guard their property ferociously, he observed, yet allow anyone to plunder their time, the one possession that cannot be replaced. The wealthy Roman distracted by clients, banquets, and political anxieties was, in Seneca's accounting, poorer than he knew: "He who is everywhere is nowhere."

The essay has acquired an uncomfortable new precision. Seneca's plunderers were at least visible — the demanding patron, the tedious dinner. Ours are engineered. The contemporary attention economy comprises thousands of the world's most sophisticated engineers whose explicit professional objective is the capture of human attention, optimized through billions of real-time experiments. The slot-machine cadence of the notification, the bottomless scroll, the autoplaying next episode — each is a precision instrument aimed at exactly the resource Seneca begged his readers to defend. He warned against squandering time; he did not foresee an industry whose revenue is the squandering.

The Stoic's deeper point, however, cuts beneath the technology. The distracted life, Seneca insisted, is not merely inefficient but unlived: preoccupation hollows out experience from within, so that a man may die old having scarcely existed. Modern cognitive research supplies the mechanism he lacked. Attention is not a spotlight aimed at a pre-existing world; it is closer to the chisel that carves experience itself. What we attend to is, experientially speaking, what happens to us. A life of fragmented attention is therefore not a full life poorly recorded — it is a fragmented life.

Seneca's remedy was not withdrawal but deliberateness: the regular retreat into study, reflection, and conversation with the great minds of the past — activities that consolidate a self rather than scattering it. The modern translations are unglamorous: the phone in another room, the single task honored to completion, the book read deeply rather than the feed grazed endlessly.

His conclusion required no update at all. Life is long enough, generously long, for the person who governs it. The question his essay presses across twenty centuries is simply whether anyone — emperor or student — is willing to do the governing.`,
