    emoji: "👓",
    genre: "教育・認知",
    words: 380,
    desc: "深い読みの神経科学と読書脳の変容を論じる読み物。",
    text: `The neuroscientist Maryanne Wolf opens her research with a fact most readers never consider: the brain was never built to read. Unlike speech, which evolution wired into us over millions of years, reading is a cultural invention barely five thousand years old — far too recent for genetic accommodation. Every reading brain must therefore be constructed individually, in childhood, by forging connections among circuits that evolved for other purposes: vision, language, memory. This construction is one of humanity's great cognitive achievements. It is also, Wolf warns, reversible.

The concern centers on what she calls deep reading: the slow, immersive processing through which readers move beyond decoding words to inference, critical analysis, and that distinctive imaginative transport in which one inhabits another's perspective for two hundred pages. These capacities are not automatic features of literacy. They are expensive habits, built through thousands of hours of sustained attention to demanding text — and like any expensive habit, they atrophy without exercise.

The digital reading environment, Wolf and others argue, trains a different and competing style. Screen reading skews measurably toward skimming: eye-tracking studies reveal an "F-pattern" in which readers consume the first lines, then race down the left margin, sampling. The medium rewards this — infinite text, embedded links, ambient notifications — and the style, practiced for hours daily, does not stay quarantined on the screen. Readers increasingly report the experience Wolf documents in herself: returning to a once-loved demanding novel and finding the sustained mode unavailable, the eyes sliding, the mind demanding the next stimulus. Studies of reading comprehension show modest but consistent advantages for paper over screens with longer, more complex texts — a gap researchers attribute partly to the skimming habits the digital medium installs.

What hangs in the balance is more than literary pleasure. The deep-reading circuit, Wolf argues, is where private reflection and empathic imagination get their most rigorous training; a society that loses the patience for difficult text loses rehearsal space for difficult thought.

Her prescription is not retreat but bilingualism: deliberately maintaining both modes — the quick scan for the world's torrent, and protected, daily passages of slow print for everything the torrent cannot carry.

The reading brain was built by culture. What culture built, only culture can keep.`,
