    desc: "忘却曲線と間隔反復の科学を解説する学習読み物。",
    text: `In the 1880s, the German psychologist Hermann Ebbinghaus performed one of science's great acts of methodological masochism: he memorized thousands of meaningless syllables — "WID," "ZOF," "KEB" — and tested his own recall at intervals, for years, alone. From this heroic tedium emerged the forgetting curve, a finding so robust it has survived fourteen decades of replication: memory for new material collapses exponentially, with the steepest losses in the first hours and days, before the curve flattens into a long, shallow decline.

The curve's shape carries an inconvenient verdict for how most of the world studies. The single intensive session — the all-night cram — deposits material at the top of the steepest slope; within days, the majority has drained away, however triumphant the next morning's exam felt. The exam may even be passed; the learning, measured weeks later, has largely evaporated.

But Ebbinghaus's data concealed a second discovery, now ranked among the most validated effects in cognitive science: each act of recalling material resets the forgetting curve — and resets it flatter. Reviewed just as it is about to slip away, a memory returns stronger and decays more slowly than before. Repeating this at expanding intervals — a day, then three, then a week, then a month — is the spacing effect, and its advantage over massed practice appears in hundreds of studies across ages, subjects, and species. The same hours, redistributed, can multiply long-term retention.

The mechanism appears to involve desirable difficulty: retrieval that requires effort strengthens memory far more than fluent re-reading, which produces familiarity's warm glow without its substance. Forgetting, counterintuitively, is the partner of durable learning — the slight slippage between sessions is precisely what makes each retrieval a workout rather than a glance.

Modern software has industrialized the insight. Spaced-repetition systems track every item's personal forgetting curve and schedule reviews at the moment of optimal difficulty — the method behind medical students absorbing pharmacology and language learners holding ten thousand words.

The strategic lesson costs nothing and applies everywhere: study less per sitting, across more sittings, and test yourself rather than re-read. Ebbinghaus's syllables were meaningless. The curve they revealed governs everything you will ever try to keep.`,
