    words: 375,
    desc: "歓待の倫理を文明史的に考察するエッセイ。客人と他者への義務。",
    text: `In the Odyssey, characters repeatedly face a stranger at the threshold without knowing who he is — and the poem judges them by what they do next. The good households feed the wanderer before asking his name; the monstrous ones devour or enslave him. The Greeks called the obligation xenia — guest-friendship — and held it sacred to Zeus himself. The pattern is not Greek but human: desert Bedouin tradition feeds even an enemy for three days; the Hebrew Bible commands love of the stranger thirty-six times, more than any other injunction; Sanskrit declares the guest a god.

The universality has a practical archaeology. In the ancient world — without hotels, police, or embassies — every traveler was utterly exposed, and every household would someday produce a traveler. Hospitality functioned as distributed insurance: I shelter your wanderer today against the day mine knocks at your door. The codes' extravagance — feed first, question later — guarded the system against its central ambiguity: the stranger, by definition, arrives unverified. Hospitality is risk formalized into virtue.

It is precisely this acceptance of risk that gives the tradition its philosophical weight. The philosopher Emmanuel Levinas built an entire ethics on the encounter with "the face of the other" — the claim that the stranger's sheer presence, before any contract or commonality, constitutes a demand. Jacques Derrida pressed the logic to its paradox: hospitality measured out, conditioned, and screened is barely hospitality at all; yet hospitality without limit dissolves the very home that makes welcome possible. Every society, he argued, lives suspended between these poles, and its position on the spectrum is among the deepest facts about it.

The ancient question has not aged; it has scaled. Refugees at borders, migrants at sea, newcomers in the neighborhood — modern states debate in the language of policy what Homer's households decided at the door, and the underlying issue is unchanged: what is owed to the person who arrives unverified, carrying only need?

The old codes offer no policy. They offer an orientation, repeated across every civilization that left records: that the knock at the door is not an interruption of the moral life but its examination — and that we are scored, as Homer scored his households, before we learn the stranger's name.`,
