    desc: "「お湯が先に凍る」謎から科学の方法を考える読み物。",
    text: `In 1963, a Tanzanian schoolboy named Erasto Mpemba noticed that his hot ice-cream mixture froze faster than his classmates' cooled ones. When he raised the observation in physics class, he was laughed at: everyone knew hot liquid must first become cold liquid, and therefore could never win a freezing race. Mpemba persisted — through ridicule that followed him between schools — until a visiting university physicist, Denis Osborne, took the question seriously, tested it, and published the results jointly with the student. The counterintuitive phenomenon now bears the boy's name: the Mpemba effect.

The first delight of the story is that the observation was ancient. Aristotle mentioned it; Francis Bacon and Descartes recorded it. Then organized science, armed with thermodynamics, quietly dismissed what fishermen and confectioners kept seeing — until a teenager's stubbornness forced the question back onto the table.

The second delight is that the effect remains genuinely contested. Decades of experiments have produced a catalogue of candidate mechanisms — evaporation reducing the hot sample's mass, dissolved gases driven off by heating, convection currents that persist and transport heat efficiently, supercooling behaving differently in previously heated water — and, awkwardly, some careful studies that fail to find the effect at all, suggesting it appears only under particular conditions that remain imperfectly mapped. Water, the most familiar substance on Earth, still keeps secrets.

But the durable value of the story is methodological, and it generalizes far beyond freezers. Science's public image is a parade of confirmations; its actual engine is the anomaly — the data point that refuses the curve. The history of discovery is substantially a history of dignified attention paid to undignified observations: penicillin from a contaminated dish, cosmic background radiation from what was assumed to be pigeon droppings in an antenna, the ozone hole flagged by readings so low the software had been discarding them as errors.

Anomalies are cheap; most dissolve into mistake or noise. The expensive commodity is the response Osborne modeled and Mpemba's teachers failed: the willingness to say "interesting" before "impossible."

Every freezer, the physicists like to note, may still contain a small unresolved research problem. So, the story suggests, may every classroom — sitting in the back row, hand half-raised, deciding whether the laughter is worth it.`,
