    words: 385,
    desc: "ナッジ理論と選択設計の倫理を論じる行動経済学読み物。",
    text: `Two European countries ask drivers about organ donation. In one, donors check a box to opt in; consent hovers near fifteen percent. In its neighbor, citizens are donors unless they check a box to opt out; consent exceeds ninety-eight. The populations are culturally similar; the difference is one default setting on one form. Multiply this discovery across every menu, ballot, contract, and app screen in modern life, and you arrive at the unsettling insight of behavioral economics: there is no neutral way to present a choice — and whoever designs the presentation holds quiet power over the outcome.

Richard Thaler and Cass Sunstein named this terrain choice architecture, and its master tool the nudge: an adjustment to how options are arranged that predictably shifts behavior without forbidding anything or changing prices. The cafeteria places fruit at eye level and dessert in the back; enrollment in retirement savings becomes automatic with freedom to leave; the tax letter mentions that most neighbors have already paid. Each intervention exploits documented regularities of the mind — inertia, loss aversion, social proof, the gravitational pull of defaults — and each preserves, formally, complete freedom of choice. Thaler and Sunstein called the philosophy "libertarian paternalism," a phrase engineered to annoy both halves of its audience.

The successes are substantial: automatic pension enrollment has raised savings rates dramatically; redesigned forms have increased college attendance among poor students; default generic prescriptions have saved health systems fortunes. Governments from Britain to Japan now operate dedicated "nudge units."

The critique is equally serious. Who nudges the nudgers? The same architecture that steers citizens toward savings steers them, in commercial hands, toward subscriptions they forget to cancel and privacy terms they never read — the manipulative variant now called sludge and dark patterns. Critics add a deeper worry: a state that achieves its ends through psychological steering bypasses the public reasoning that democratic persuasion requires; the citizen is managed rather than convinced.

The defenders' strongest reply remains the opening observation: the choice between nudging and not nudging does not exist. Some default will be set; some option will be listed first.

The architecture is being drawn either way. The only live question is whether its blueprints are examined — and whom the building ultimately serves.`,
