    desc: "数学者が語る「美しい証明」とは何かを探る読み物。",
    text: `Ask working mathematicians why they chose their field, and the answer that recurs is not utility but beauty. The claim puzzles outsiders, for whom mathematics is the memory of formulas under fluorescent light. Yet the aesthetic vocabulary of mathematics is precise, consistent across cultures, and — recent neuroscience suggests — literally accurate: brain imaging of mathematicians contemplating equations they rate as beautiful shows activation in the same region that responds to great music and painting.

What do mathematicians mean by beauty? The consensus criteria are surprisingly specific. Economy: a beautiful proof achieves its result with astonishing brevity of means — nothing wasted, nothing decorative. Surprise: it connects territories believed distant, as Euler's identity binds five fundamental constants from separate continents of mathematics into one equation that the mathematician Richard Feynman called "the most remarkable formula." Inevitability: once seen, the argument feels as though it could not have been otherwise — the shock of the surprising fused with the click of the necessary. The mathematician G. H. Hardy, whose essay "A Mathematician's Apology" remains the canonical text, added depth and seriousness: beautiful mathematics touches load-bearing ideas, not peripheral curiosities.

The canonical specimen is Euclid's proof, twenty-three centuries old, that the prime numbers never end. Suppose they do; multiply the entire finite list together and add one. This new number, divided by any prime on the list, leaves remainder one — so either it is itself a new prime, or it is divisible by a prime missing from the supposedly complete list. Either way, the list fails. Contradiction; the primes are infinite. Four sentences, no machinery beyond multiplication, and a result about infinity itself — economy, surprise, inevitability, depth, all present.

Hardy drew a stark conclusion: real mathematics, like painting and poetry, needs no defense beyond its beauty — adding, with satisfaction, that his own number theory would never have practical use. History supplied the ironic footnote: that "useless" number theory now encrypts every online transaction on Earth.

The pattern repeats so reliably that physicists speak of mathematics' "unreasonable effectiveness." The universe, for reasons no one fully understands, seems to favor the beautiful equations — as though elegance were not a human taste at all, but a property of reality awaiting discovery.`,
