    id: 154, level: 5,
    title: "The Tyranny of Metrics",
    emoji: "📊",
    genre: "社会・組織",
    words: 380,
    desc: "数値評価への過度な依存が組織を歪める仕組みを解説。",
    text: `A surgeon declines a difficult patient. A school redefines its curriculum around a standardized test. A police department reclassifies thefts to flatter its statistics. These scenes from unrelated institutions share a single underlying mechanism, one the historian Jerry Z. Muller has called the tyranny of metrics: the modern conviction that numerical measurement, tied to rewards and punishments, is the universal solvent for problems of judgment and trust — and the systematic damage that conviction inflicts.

The pattern was codified independently by an economist and a psychologist, and now bears both their names. Goodhart's law: when a measure becomes a target, it ceases to be a good measure. Campbell's law adds the corollary: the more a metric is used for high-stakes decisions, the more it will be gamed, and the more it will distort the process it monitors. The logic is almost thermodynamic. Any metric is a proxy — a thin, countable slice of a thick, valuable thing. Attach consequences to the proxy, and human ingenuity flows toward the slice: teaching to the test rather than educating, treating the survival statistic rather than the patient, optimizing the response-time number while the underlying service decays. The measured part flourishes; the unmeasured whole quietly starves.

The most corrosive cost is the substitution of measurement for trust. Metric regimes typically arrive as accountability reforms, born of legitimate suspicion toward unaccountable expertise. But the audit apparatus itself consumes the professionals' time, signals institutional distrust, and drives out precisely the intrinsic motivation — craftsmanship, vocation, care — that made the work good before it was counted. Muller documents the spiral: distrust produces metrics; metrics produce gaming; gaming confirms distrust; distrust produces more metrics.

None of this convicts measurement itself, and the critics are explicit on the point: the alternative to bad metrics is not ignorance but judgment — numbers used as instruments of inquiry rather than verdicts, interpreted by people who understand what the proxy omits, with stakes low enough that the measure can stay honest.

The discipline reduces to two questions, worth asking of every dashboard: What does this number not see? And what will people do to it once their salaries depend on it?

What gets measured gets managed, says the slogan. What gets measured also gets gamed — and what cannot be measured gets forgotten.`,
