    words: 380,
    desc: "イエローストーンのオオカミ再導入から生態系の連鎖を学ぶ読み物。",
    text: `In 1995, after a seventy-year absence, wolves were released back into Yellowstone National Park. What followed has become ecology's most celebrated story — and, in its refined retelling, one of its most instructive lessons about how nature's complexity resists even our best narratives.

The popular version is majestic. The returning wolves thinned and redirected the elk herds that had, unchecked, grazed the park's valleys bare. Willows and aspens resurged along the streams. Beavers returned to the recovered willows, and their dams re-engineered the waterways — cooling pools, raising water tables, multiplying habitat for fish, amphibians, and songbirds. Even the rivers, the story goes, changed course as vegetation stabilized the banks: a single predator, restored, cascading downward through the food web to redraw the landscape itself. Ecologists call the mechanism a trophic cascade, and Yellowstone became its global showcase — evidence that ecosystems are held in shape from the top, and that removing apex predators quietly unravels them.

The refined version, assembled by two further decades of fieldwork, is humbler and more interesting. The cascade is real but partial and patchy: willows recovered vigorously in some drainages and barely in others; elk numbers were driven down by hunting, drought, and bears as well as wolves; the beavers needed reintroduction help of their own. Some researchers argue the ecosystem crossed thresholds during the wolfless decades that no reintroduction can fully reverse — that ecological damage can be locked in, like a dislocated joint that heals wrong. The honest summary: wolves were necessary for the recovery, and not sufficient.

Both versions matter, because rewilding — the deliberate restoration of self-regulating wilderness, from European bison in Romania to jaguars in Argentina — has become conservation's boldest program. The simple Yellowstone story supplies its inspiration; the complicated one supplies its instruction manual. Ecosystems are not machines awaiting a missing part, but histories — path-dependent, surprise-generating, only partially steerable.

The deepest shift rewilding demands is in the steward's self-image: from gardener, arranging a fixed display, to something more like a physician of systems — intervening decisively, then standing back to let a complexity beyond full comprehension resume its own work.

The wolves, indifferent to all narratives about them, continue hunting the valleys either way.`,
